					<TD style="background: #333333;" valign=top>
						<IMG src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/posticon.gif" border=0> posted 2004-11-16 09:43&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
 						<A href="edit.php?board=player&id=12529"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			 			<A href="reply.php?board=player&id=12529"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A> </FONT>
			  			<HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  			To Whom it May Concern (Including my council mates in The Spawn):<br />
<br />
I am quitting this game.<br />
<br />
After much time spent trying to get decent fleets, researching, trying to train my commies through missions, blockades, etc, just to see them killed, I have hit my limit.<br />
<br />
This game is probably one of the least friendly to new players I have ever seen.  There is an immence amount of information to read through and people who misinform you as to how to play the game.  There is almost no documentation to determine what you ought to be doing, just tons of text of explanations of issues that don't really matter.  How should any noob realize that weakers weapons don't matter?  How many times have I seen someone try to prove through the math of the numbers that many smaller ships ought to be able to beat one big one.  Of course, it's not true, but people want to believe it.  <br />
<br />
It is pretty simple, really.  Start at the beginning of the set.  Research very quickly till you can have HBH/DB with Eternium/WoK.  Then leach off of smaller players, trying to avoid the attention of those larger than yourself.  If you're big enough, you don't have to worry.  <br />
<br />
But if you're small, or new, it's nearly impossible to determine how this all should work.  More than that, it's nearly impossible to get a decent defense up, as once you're big enough to be building fleets of dooms, all of your commanders are always killed by people twice your size.<br />
<br />
Lest you all think I am some blabbering idiot who didn't take enough time to learn the game, I did manage to reach the top 50 in rankings before I quit (with only fleets of dooms, no fluffing).  I did figure out the researching bit, and I got some good planets (and managed to hold on to quite a few of the R/UR's).  I just am sick of trying (over and over again) to get a decent fleet built up, only to see all my good commanders killed by some jerk who needed to get his level 19 up to a level 20.  <br />
<br />
<br />
People talk about wanting to expand the playing base.  This will never happen unless a number of things change:<br />
<br />
1) A more friendly player base.  This is key.  If you're not one of the vets, you're not welcome.  This will NEVER attract new players.<br />
<br />
2) Better bottom-feeding rules.  If noobs realize that they'll never have a chance to have a full fleet of 40 dooms, they'll quit before they even realize how to play.<br />
<br />
3) A better explanation of the game.  Yeah, there's the guide, but I think that most people will agree that most of the guide is either fluff or crap.  The good parts are either buried or not written (otherwise how would the good players stay on top?).  And is the most recent guide even the one linked to on the main page?  <br />
<br />
4) A generally more complex game.  Right now, it's pretty simple, a race to HBH dooms.  The first one there pretty much wins.  If you get lucky and get some HUR's along the way (and don't get them raped by someone else), you'll land in a good spot.  Then, you'll be able to bottom feed off of everyone else, raping those smaller than you.  You'll be unbeatable.  And no thinking was involved.  Right now, the only way to be good at this game is to be online constantly, and to play without any respect of everyone else.  If more playing strategies were viable, more people would play.  <br />
<br />
<br />
But alas, it does not seem that these changes will ever be implemented (just look at the thread complaining about 10 min turns, which would have made the game at least a little more accessable).  <br />
<br />
Go ahead, flame me now, call me stupid, call me a noob.  Whatever.  I'm done with this game...it's not worth it any more.  Too much spite, too little thinking.<br />
<br />
AM will die without changes, and I don't want to be a part of it's sinking ship.						<P align=right> </P>
					</TD>
				</TR>
	
		
